##  5. Security Defaults vs. Conditional Access

Every tenant needs a baseline level of security right out of the box. Microsoft provides this via **Security Defaults**.

| Feature | Security Defaults | Conditional Access (CA) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Licensing** | Free / Included with all tiers | Requires Entra ID Premium P1/P2 |
| **Flexibility** | All-or-nothing (Turned on or off) | Highly customizable policies |
| **MFA Enforcement** | Enforces MFA for *all* users | Enforces MFA based on conditions (Location, Device, Risk) |
| **Legacy Auth** | Blocks legacy protocols completely | Can selectively block or allow |

> 🚨 **Exam Alert:** You **cannot** use Security Defaults and Conditional Access policies at the same time. If you want to write custom Conditional Access rules, you must turn off Security Defaults first.
